{{Infobox motorsport championship | name = Formula Ford Championship of Great Britain | logo = Formula Ford GB Logo 2012.jpg | image-size = 250px | caption = | category = [[Open wheel car|Single seaters]] | country/region = {{GBR}} | inaugural = 1976 | folded = 2014 | classes = | drivers = | teams = | constructors = [[Mygale]], Sinter | engines = [[Ford]] | tyres = [[Dunlop Tyres]], [[Hankook]] | champion driver = {{flagicon|ZAF}} [[Jayde Kruger]] | champion team = {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Joe Tandy|JTR]] }}
The '''British Formula Ford Championship''' was an entry level [[single seater]] motor sport category, designed to give racing drivers their first step into car racing after [[karting]]. Drivers from across the world were attracted to the [[United Kingdom]] to compete in the series, and successful [[Formula One]] drivers such as [[Ayrton Senna]] and [[Jenson Button]] won their first single-seater titles in the championship. The championship was run to various [[Formula Ford]] regulations over the years, based on the engines provided for the championship by [[Ford Motor Company]]. These engine based regulations/specifications include the [[Ford Kent engine]], [[Ford Zetec engine]], [[Ford Duratec engine]] and in the final years the [[Ford EcoBoost engine]].
From the 2015 season onwards, the championship will be replaced by [[MSA Formula]], which conforms to the FIA's new [[Formula 4]] regulations. Many of the teams and drivers which competed in the final season of British Formula Ford will move to the new series.
==History== [[File:Formula Ford Duratec .4.jpg|thumb|Formula Ford Duratec car from [[Mygale]], [[Ray Formula Cars|Ray]] and [[Van Diemen]]]] Although the first British Formula Ford Championship was not held until 1976, Formula Ford's roots are firmly situated in the British racing scene. The first Formula Ford race was held at [[Brands Hatch]] in 1967 and was the precursor to the birth of the domestic championship. The first British Formula Ford Championship, held in 1976, was the original Formula Ford Championship which gave birth to many others over the years, including successful championships in [[Australian Formula Ford Championship|Australia]] and [[New Zealand Formula Ford Championship|New Zealand]].<ref name=FFhistory>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishformulaford.com/history|title=The History of Formula Ford Racing|publisher=[britishformulaford.com]|accessdate=30 October 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016042737/http://www.britishformulaford.com/history|archivedate=16 October 2012|df=}}</ref>
The championship started out with the 1600cc [[Ford Kent engine]] and continued to use it until [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] introduced its newer, more powerful 1800cc [[Ford Zetec engine]]. Although this engine change didn't affect the other technical regulations, which still called for steel [[space frame]]s which were much more economical to build and run compared to their [[carbon fiber]] counterparts, the increased engine power accelerated chassis development, causing many of the smaller manufacturers stopped producing cars, resulting in fewer constructors represented in the championship.<ref name=zetechistory>{{cite news|url=http://www.formulafordzetec.co.uk/formula_ford_zetec_004.htm|title=History |publisher=[formulafordzetec.co.uk]|accessdate=30 October 2012}}</ref> The Zetec regulations lasted only 12 years up until the [[Ford Duratec engine]] was introduced in 2006, providing better handling and power due to its lighter weight even though the specification had returned to 1600cc engines.<ref name=FFhistory/>
The biggest changes to the championship came in [[2012 British Formula Ford Championship|2012]] when the latest [[Ford EcoBoost engine]] and specification was adopted as the main championship. The EcoBoost car marks a substantial change in the direction of Formula Ford racing as it introduces both smaller capacity [[Turbocharged petrol engines]] and for the first time a [[Sequential manual transmission|sequential gearbox]].<ref name=zetechistory/>
==The car== [[File:Formula Ford Ecoboost 2012 4.jpg|thumb|2012 Formula Ford EcoBoost Car]] The championship currently allows two specification of [[Formula Ford]] car to race: the current generation EcoBoost car and the previous generation Duratec car. The championship is multi-chassis, featuring manufacturers such as [[Van Diemen]] and [[Mygale]]. To help keep costs low, cars are made from steel, as opposed to the more exotic carbon fibre commonly found in higher categories of racing. The Duratec cars were introduced in 2006, when all the cars in the series were required to use the 1600cc [[Naturally aspirated engine|Naturally aspirated]] [[Ford Duratec engine]] which replaced the [[Ford Kent engine]] that had been used since the championships inception. Beginning in [[2012 British Formula Ford Championship|2012]], the EcoBoost class was introduced to run as the premier class alongside a secondary class for the aging Duratec cars. The EcoBoost class utilises Ford's latest [[Ford EcoBoost engine|EcoBoost engine]] which provides greater power thanks to the introduction of a [[Turbocharged petrol engines|Turbo Charger]]. The chassis however remains a steel [[space frame]] rather than the [[carbon fibre]] [[Monocoque]] found in other formulae.<ref name=2012regs/>
From 2015 onwards, the MSA Formula will use [[Formula 4]] regulations. [[Mygale]] will continue to provide the carbon-fibre monocoque chassis (As opposed to the [[Tatuus]] supplied chassis used in [[BRDC Formula 4 Championship|BRDC F4]]. The engine will be a [[Ford]] 1.6L [[EcoBoost]] engine as used in the more modern Formula Ford cars, tuned to a maximum of 160 PS. All engines will be tuned by the same race engine preparer, in an attempt to reduce costs. Similarly, all tyres will be provided by [[Hankook]]. Sadev will provide the sequential paddle shift transmission and data logging system.
==The Championship== From 2013, the championship is composed of 30 rounds held at ten events in support of the [[British Touring Car Championship]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=3211 |title=Formula Ford returns in 2013 |work=[[British Touring Car Championship]] |publisher=[[TOCA]] |date=12 October 2012 |accessdate=12 October 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723101130/http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=3211 |archivedate=23 July 2013 |df= }}</ref> Both EcoBoost and Duratec classes compete in the same races as each other. Drivers who have competed in less than 4 junior formula races in the past are eligible to compete for the Rookie Cup, whilst both Teams and Constructors have separate championships for themselves. The Nations Cup is awarded to the highest placed registered driver from each country excluding UK.<ref name=2012regs>{{cite news|url=http://www.brscc.co.uk/assets/2012-dunlopmsaformulafordchampionshipofgbregulations-msa-approved--copy.pdf|title=2012 Formula Ford GB Regulations|work=British Formula Ford Championship|publisher=[[BRSCC]]|accessdate=29 October 2012}}</ref> In 2015, the series will again run 30 rounds at ten events in support of the BTCC, despite becoming the MSA Formula.
===Weekend Format=== A 20-minute qualifying session is used to decide the grid for the all the weekends races. The drivers fastest lap decides the grid for race one, their second fastest time decides the grid for race two and their third fastest time, the grid for race three. All three races will be run over 15 miles.<ref name=2012regs/>
