The '''Facebook privacy and copyright hoaxes''' are a collection of similar [[internet hoax]]es that claim that posting a status on social networking site [[Facebook]] constitutes a privacy notice that protects your posts on the site from [[copyright infringement]]<ref name=schupak>{{cite web | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/facebook-privacy-hoax-making-the-rounds-again/ | title=Facebook privacy hoax making the rounds, again | work=CBS News | date=5 January 2015 | accessdate=11 December 2015 | author=Schupak, Amanda}}</ref> or that provides privacy protection to their profile information and other content they have posted to the site. The hoax takes the form of a Facebook status that, when posted, urges others to post the same or a similar status.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/viral-facebook-privacy-notice-is-a-hoax/ | title=Viral "Facebook privacy notice" is a hoax | work=CBS News | date=26 November 2012 | accessdate=11 December 2015 | author=Ngak, Chenga}}</ref><ref name=wired>{{cite web | url=https://www.wired.com/2012/11/facebook-copyright-hoax/ | title=Facebook Debunks Copyright Hoax | work=Wired | date=26 November 2012 | accessdate=11 December 2015 | author=Tate, Ryan}}</ref> The hoax first became popular in May and June 2012, but has since re-appeared multiple times, including in November 2012<ref name=wired/> and then again in 2015, first in January<ref name=schupak/> and later in September of that year.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/dont-fall-for-this-facebook-privacy-hoax-again/ | title=Watch out for these Facebook privacy hoaxes | work=CBS News | date=28 September 2015 | accessdate=11 December 2015 | author=Earl, Jennifer}}</ref> All of the hoaxes are based on several misunderstandings, including, with respect to the privacy version, the fact that it incorrectly assumes that Facebook becoming a [[public company]] in May 2012 affects how it treats user information,<ref name=slate>{{cite web | url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/future_tense/2012/06/05/facebook_privacy_notice_debunked_.html | title=Don't Bother Posting the "Facebook Privacy Notice" That's Spreading Around | work=Slate | date=5 June 2012 | accessdate=11 December 2015 | author=Sydiongco, David}}</ref> the assumption that posting certain content online can protect someone from adverse legal consequences,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snopes.com/computer/facebook/privacy.asp | title=Facebook Privacy Notice | work=Snopes | date=28 September 2015 | accessdate=11 December 2015}}</ref> and the fact that the hoax ignores that if Facebook wanted to significantly change its terms of service agreement, it would have to provide notification of these changes.<ref name=slate/>

